# AI Engineering Standards

## Purpose
Define safe, maintainable patterns for LLM integration and Context-Augmented Generation.

## Rules
- Centralize model provider access in `app/services/` or a dedicated client module if the project grows.
- Do not call OpenAI or Anthropic directly from route handlers.
- Keep provider, model, timeout, and API keys configurable through settings.
- Default to low-cost models for exercises unless stronger reasoning is explicitly required.
- Store reusable prompt context in clear modules such as `app/context/examples.py`.
- Treat LLM responses as untrusted external input.
- Validate or normalize model outputs before returning them from the API when structure matters.
- Add deterministic tests around prompt construction, context injection, parsing, and fallback logic.
- Mock provider clients in tests.

## Provider Defaults
- Use `OPENAI_API_KEY` from the environment.
- Use `OPENAI_MODEL`, initially `gpt-4o-mini`.
- If Anthropic is added, use `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` and a low-cost Haiku model.
- Use `LLM_PROVIDER` only when more than one provider is implemented.

## CAG Guidance
- Inject static examples deliberately, not as hidden global magic.
- Keep examples representative of the task.
- Make the system prompt explain how examples should influence the answer.
- Keep context small enough to understand and maintain manually.

## Checklist
- [ ] Provider access is centralized.
- [ ] Model calls have timeout and error handling.
- [ ] Static context is explicit and reviewable.
- [ ] LLM output is validated or safely returned as text.
- [ ] Tests mock external provider calls.
- [ ] Prompt-critical logic does not live only in a notebook.

